30Expr native_interleave(const Expr &x) {
31 string fn;
32 switch (x.type().bits()) {
33 case 8:
34 fn = "halide.hexagon.interleave.vb";
35 break;
36 case 16:
37 fn = "halide.hexagon.interleave.vh";
38 break;
39 case 32:
40 fn = "halide.hexagon.interleave.vw";
41 break;
42 default:
43 internal_error << "Cannot interleave native vectors of type " << x.type() << "\n";
44 }
45 return Call::make(x.type(), fn, {x}, Call::PureExtern);
46}
47
48Expr native_deinterleave(const Expr &x) {
49 string fn;
50 switch (x.type().bits()) {
51 case 8:
52 fn = "halide.hexagon.deinterleave.vb";
53 break;
54 case 16:
55 fn = "halide.hexagon.deinterleave.vh";
56 break;
57 case 32:
58 fn = "halide.hexagon.deinterleave.vw";
59 break;
60 default:
61 internal_error << "Cannot deinterleave native vectors of type " << x.type() << "\n";
62 }
63 return Call::make(x.type(), fn, {x}, Call::PureExtern);
64}

66bool is_native_interleave_op(const Expr &x, const char *name) {
67 const Call *c = x.as<Call>();
68 if (!c || c->args.size() != 1) {
69 return false;
70 }
71 return starts_with(c->name, name);
72}

74bool is_native_interleave(const Expr &x) {
75 return is_native_interleave_op(x, "halide.hexagon.interleave");

82string type_suffix(Type type, bool signed_variants) {
83 string prefix = type.is_vector() ? ".v" : ".";
84 if (type.is_int() || !signed_variants) {
85 switch (type.bits()) {
86 case 8:
87 return prefix + "b";
88 case 16:
89 return prefix + "h";
90 case 32:
91 return prefix + "w";
92 }
93 } else if (type.is_uint()) {
94 switch (type.bits()) {
95 case 8:
96 return prefix + "ub";
97 case 16:
98 return prefix + "uh";
99 case 32:
100 return prefix + "uw";
101 }
102 }
103 internal_error << "Unsupported HVX type: " << type << "\n";
104 return "";
105}
106
107string type_suffix(const Expr &a, bool signed_variants) {
108 return type_suffix(a.type(), signed_variants);
109}
110
111string type_suffix(const Expr &a, const Expr &b, bool signed_variants) {
112 return type_suffix(a, signed_variants) + type_suffix(b, signed_variants);
113}
114
115string type_suffix(const vector<Expr> &ops, bool signed_variants) {
116 if (ops.empty()) {
117 return "";
118 }
119 string suffix = type_suffix(ops.front(), signed_variants);
120 for (size_t i = 1; i < ops.size(); i++) {
121 suffix = suffix + type_suffix(ops[i], signed_variants);
122 }
123 return suffix;
124}

128// Helper to handle various forms of multiplication.
129Expr as_mul(const Expr &a) {
130 if (a.as<Mul>()) {
131 return a;
132 } else if (const Call *wm = Call::as_intrinsic(a, {Call::widening_mul})) {
133 return simplify(Mul::make(cast(wm->type, wm->args[0]), cast(wm->type, wm->args[1])));
134 } else if (const Call *s = Call::as_intrinsic(a, {Call::shift_left, Call::widening_shift_left})) {
135 const uint64_t *log2_b = as_const_uint(s->args[1]);
136 if (log2_b) {
137 Expr b = make_one(s->type) << cast(UInt(s->type.bits()), (int)*log2_b);
138 return simplify(Mul::make(cast(s->type, s->args[0]), b));
139 }
140 }
141 return Expr();
142}

166struct Pattern {
167 enum Flags {
168 InterleaveResult = 1 << 0, // After evaluating the pattern, interleave native vectors of the result.
169 SwapOps01 = 1 << 1, // Swap operands 0 and 1 prior to substitution.
170 SwapOps12 = 1 << 2, // Swap operands 1 and 2 prior to substitution.
171
172 DeinterleaveOp0 = 1 << 5, // Prior to evaluating the pattern, deinterleave native vectors of operand 0.
173 DeinterleaveOp1 = 1 << 6, // Same as above, but for operand 1.
174 DeinterleaveOp2 = 1 << 7,
175 DeinterleaveOps = DeinterleaveOp0 | DeinterleaveOp1 | DeinterleaveOp2,
176
177 BeginDeinterleaveOp = 0, // BeginDeinterleaveOp and EndDeinterleaveOp ensure that we check only three
178 EndDeinterleaveOp = 3, // deinterleave Op0, 1 and 2.
179 // Many patterns are instructions that widen only
180 // operand 0, which need to both deinterleave operand 0, and then
181 // re-interleave the result.
182 ReinterleaveOp0 = InterleaveResult | DeinterleaveOp0,
183
184 NarrowOp0 = 1 << 10, // Replace operand 0 with its half-width equivalent.
185 NarrowOp1 = 1 << 11, // Same as above, but for operand 1.
186 NarrowOp2 = 1 << 12,
187 NarrowOps = NarrowOp0 | NarrowOp1 | NarrowOp2,
188
189 NarrowUnsignedOp0 = 1 << 15, // Similar to the above, but narrow to an unsigned half width type.
190 NarrowUnsignedOp1 = 1 << 16,
191 NarrowUnsignedOp2 = 1 << 17,
192 NarrowUnsignedOps = NarrowUnsignedOp0 | NarrowUnsignedOp1 | NarrowUnsignedOp2,
193
194 v65orLater = 1 << 21, // Pattern should be matched only for v65 target or later
195 v66orLater = 1 << 22, // Pattern should be matched only for v66 target or later
196 };
197
198 string intrin; // Name of the intrinsic
199 Expr pattern; // The pattern to match against
200 int flags;
201
202 Pattern() = default;
203 Pattern(const string &intrin, Expr p, int flags = 0)
204 : intrin(intrin), pattern(std::move(p)), flags(flags) {
205 }
206};

226// Check if a pattern with flags 'flags' is supported on the target.
227bool check_pattern_target(int flags, const Target &target) {
228 if ((flags & (Pattern::v65orLater)) &&
229 !target.features_any_of({Target::HVX_v65, Target::HVX_v66})) {
230 return false;
231 }
232 if ((flags & (Pattern::v66orLater)) &&
233 !target.features_any_of({Target::HVX_v66})) {
234 return false;
235 }
236 return true;
237}
238
239// Check if the matches satisfy the given pattern flags, and mutate the matches
240// as specified by the flags.
241bool process_match_flags(vector<Expr> &matches, int flags) {
242 // The Pattern::Narrow*Op* flags are ordered such that the operand
243 // corresponds to the bit (with operand 0 corresponding to the least
244 // significant bit), so we can check for them all in a loop.
245 for (size_t i = 0; i < matches.size(); i++) {
246 Type t = matches[i].type();
247 if (flags & (Pattern::NarrowOp0 << i)) {
248 matches[i] = lossless_cast(t.narrow(), matches[i]);
249 } else if (flags & (Pattern::NarrowUnsignedOp0 << i)) {
250 matches[i] = lossless_cast(t.narrow().with_code(Type::UInt), matches[i]);
251 }
252 if (!matches[i].defined()) {
253 return false;
254 }
255 }
256
257 for (size_t i = Pattern::BeginDeinterleaveOp; i < Pattern::EndDeinterleaveOp; i++) {
258 if (flags & (Pattern::DeinterleaveOp0 << (i - Pattern::BeginDeinterleaveOp))) {
259 internal_assert(matches[i].type().is_vector());
260 matches[i] = native_deinterleave(matches[i]);
261 }
262 }
263 if (flags & Pattern::SwapOps01) {
264 internal_assert(matches.size() >= 2);
265 std::swap(matches[0], matches[1]);
266 }
267 if (flags & Pattern::SwapOps12) {
268 internal_assert(matches.size() >= 3);
269 std::swap(matches[1], matches[2]);
270 }
271 return true;
272}
273
274// Replace an expression with the one specified by a pattern.
275Expr replace_pattern(Expr x, const vector<Expr> &matches, const Pattern &p) {
276 x = Call::make(x.type(), p.intrin, matches, Call::PureExtern);
277 if (p.flags & Pattern::InterleaveResult) {
278 // The pattern wants us to interleave the result.
279 x = native_interleave(x);
280 }
281 return x;
282}

284bool is_double_vector(const Expr &x, const Target &target) {
285 int native_vector_lanes = target.natural_vector_size(x.type());
286 return x.type().lanes() % (2 * native_vector_lanes) == 0;
287}
288
289// Attempt to apply one of the patterns to x. If a match is
290// successful, the expression is replaced with a call using the
291// matched operands. Prior to substitution, the matches are mutated
292// with op_mutator.
293Expr apply_patterns(Expr x, const vector<Pattern> &patterns, const Target &target, IRMutator *op_mutator) {
294 constexpr int debug_level = 3;
295 debug(debug_level) << "apply_patterns " << x << "\n";
296 vector<Expr> matches;
297 for (const Pattern &p : patterns) {
298 if (!check_pattern_target(p.flags, target)) {
299 continue;
300 }
301
302 if (expr_match(p.pattern, x, matches)) {
303 debug(debug_level) << "matched " << p.pattern << "\n";
304 debug(debug_level) << "matches:\n";
305 for (const Expr &i : matches) {
306 debug(debug_level) << i << "\n";
307 }
308
309 if (!process_match_flags(matches, p.flags)) {
310 continue;
311 }
312
313 // Don't apply pattern if it involves an interleave,
314 // and is not a multiple of two vectors.
315 // See https://github.com/halide/Halide/issues/1582
316 if ((p.flags & Pattern::InterleaveResult) && !is_double_vector(x, target)) {
317 continue;
318 }
319 // Mutate the operands with the given mutator.
320 for (Expr &op : matches) {
321 op = op_mutator->mutate(op);
322 }
323
324 x = replace_pattern(x, matches, p);
325 debug(debug_level) << "rewrote to: " << x << "\n";
326 return x;
327 }
328 }
329 return x;
330}
331
332template<typename T>
333Expr apply_commutative_patterns(const T *op, const vector<Pattern> &patterns, const Target &target, IRMutator *mutator) {
334 Expr ret = apply_patterns(op, patterns, target, mutator);
335 if (!ret.same_as(op)) {
336 return ret;
337 }
338
339 // Try commuting the op
340 Expr commuted = T::make(op->b, op->a);
341 ret = apply_patterns(commuted, patterns, target, mutator);
342 if (!ret.same_as(commuted)) {
343 return ret;
344 }
345
346 return op;
347}

349typedef pair<Expr, Expr> MulExpr;
350
351// If ty is scalar or a vector with different lanes count,
352// and x is a vector, try to remove a broadcast or adjust
353// the number of lanes in Broadcast or indices in a Shuffle
354// to match the ty lanes before using lossless_cast on it.
355Expr unbroadcast_lossless_cast(Type ty, Expr x) {
356 if (x.type().is_vector()) {
357 if (const Broadcast *bc = x.as<Broadcast>()) {
358 if (ty.is_scalar()) {
359 x = bc->value;
360 } else {
361 x = Broadcast::make(bc->value, ty.lanes());
362 }
363 }
364 // Check if shuffle can be treated as a broadcast.
365 if (const Shuffle *shuff = x.as<Shuffle>()) {
366 int factor = x.type().lanes() / ty.lanes();
367 if (shuff->is_broadcast() && shuff->broadcast_factor() % factor == 0) {
368 x = Shuffle::make(shuff->vectors, std::vector<int>(shuff->indices.begin(),
369 shuff->indices.begin() + ty.lanes()));
370 }
371 }
372 }
373 if (ty.lanes() != x.type().lanes()) {
374 return Expr();
375 }
376 return lossless_cast(ty, x);
377}
378
379// Try to extract a list of multiplies of the form a_ty*b_ty added
380// together, such that op is equivalent to the sum of the
381// multiplies in 'mpys', added to 'rest'.
382// Difference in mpys.size() - return indicates the number of
383// expressions where we pretend the op to be multiplied by 1.
384int find_mpy_ops(const Expr &op, Type a_ty, Type b_ty, int max_mpy_count,
385 vector<MulExpr> &mpys, Expr &rest) {
386 if ((int)mpys.size() >= max_mpy_count) {
387 rest = rest.defined() ? Add::make(rest, op) : op;
388 return 0;
389 }
390
391 // If the add is also widening, remove the cast.
392 int mpy_bits = std::max(a_ty.bits(), b_ty.bits()) * 2;
393 Expr maybe_mul = op;
394 if (op.type().bits() == mpy_bits * 2) {
395 if (const Cast *cast = op.as<Cast>()) {
396 if (cast->value.type().bits() == mpy_bits) {
397 maybe_mul = cast->value;
398 }
399 }
400 }
401 maybe_mul = as_mul(maybe_mul);
402
403 if (maybe_mul.defined()) {
404 const Mul *mul = maybe_mul.as<Mul>();
405 Expr a = unbroadcast_lossless_cast(a_ty, mul->a);
406 Expr b = unbroadcast_lossless_cast(b_ty, mul->b);
407 if (a.defined() && b.defined()) {
408 mpys.emplace_back(a, b);
409 return 1;
410 } else {
411 // Try to commute the op.
412 a = unbroadcast_lossless_cast(a_ty, mul->b);
413 b = unbroadcast_lossless_cast(b_ty, mul->a);
414 if (a.defined() && b.defined()) {
415 mpys.emplace_back(a, b);
416 return 1;
417 }
418 }
419 } else if (const Add *add = op.as<Add>()) {
420 int mpy_count = 0;
421 mpy_count += find_mpy_ops(add->a, a_ty, b_ty, max_mpy_count, mpys, rest);
422 mpy_count += find_mpy_ops(add->b, a_ty, b_ty, max_mpy_count, mpys, rest);
423 return mpy_count;
424 } else if (const Call *add = Call::as_intrinsic(op, {Call::widening_add})) {
425 int mpy_count = 0;
426 mpy_count += find_mpy_ops(cast(op.type(), add->args[0]), a_ty, b_ty, max_mpy_count, mpys, rest);
427 mpy_count += find_mpy_ops(cast(op.type(), add->args[1]), a_ty, b_ty, max_mpy_count, mpys, rest);
428 return mpy_count;
429 }
430
431 // Attempt to pretend this op is multiplied by 1.
432 Expr as_a = unbroadcast_lossless_cast(a_ty, op);
433 Expr as_b = unbroadcast_lossless_cast(b_ty, op);
434
435 if (as_a.defined()) {
436 mpys.emplace_back(as_a, make_one(b_ty));
437 } else if (as_b.defined()) {
438 mpys.emplace_back(make_one(a_ty), as_b);
439 } else {
440 rest = rest.defined() ? Add::make(rest, op) : op;
441 }
442 return 0;
443}

445// Perform peephole optimizations on the IR, adding appropriate
446// interleave and deinterleave calls.
447class OptimizePatterns : public IRMutator {
448private:
449 using IRMutator::visit;
450
451 Scope<Interval> bounds;
452 const Target &target;
453
454 Expr visit(const Mul *op) override {
455 static const vector<Pattern> scalar_muls = {
456 // Non-widening scalar multiplication.
457 {"halide.hexagon.mul.vh.b", wild_i16x * wild_i16, Pattern::NarrowOp1},
458 {"halide.hexagon.mul.vw.h", wild_i32x * wild_i32, Pattern::NarrowOp1},
459 // TODO: There's also mul.vw.b. We currently generate mul.vw.h
460 // instead. I'm not sure mul.vw.b is faster, it might even be
461 // slower due to the extra step in broadcasting the scalar up to
462 // 32 bits.
463 };
464
465 static const vector<Pattern> muls = {
466 // One operand widening multiplication.
467 {"halide.hexagon.mul.vw.vh", wild_i32x * wild_i32x, Pattern::ReinterleaveOp0 | Pattern::NarrowOp1},
468 {"halide.hexagon.mul.vw.vuh", wild_i32x * wild_i32x, Pattern::ReinterleaveOp0 | Pattern::NarrowUnsignedOp1},
469 {"halide.hexagon.mul.vuw.vuh", wild_u32x * wild_u32x, Pattern::ReinterleaveOp0 | Pattern::NarrowUnsignedOp1},
470 };
471
472 if (op->type.is_vector()) {
473 Expr new_expr = apply_commutative_patterns(op, scalar_muls, target, this);
474 if (!new_expr.same_as(op)) {
475 return new_expr;
476 }
477
478 new_expr = apply_commutative_patterns(op, muls, target, this);
479 if (!new_expr.same_as(op)) {
480 return new_expr;
481 }
482 }
483 return IRMutator::visit(op);
484 }
485
486 // We'll try to sort the mpys based my mpys.first.
487 // But, for this all the mpy.first exprs should either be
488 // all loads or all slice_vectors.
489 static void sort_mpy_exprs(vector<MulExpr> &mpys) {
490 struct LoadCompare {
491 bool operator()(const MulExpr &m1, const MulExpr &m2) const {
492 if (!m1.first.defined() || !m2.first.defined()) {
493 return false;
494 }
495 const Load *m1_load = m1.first.as<Load>();
496 const Load *m2_load = m2.first.as<Load>();
497 internal_assert(m1_load && m2_load);
498 const Ramp *m1_ramp = m1_load->index.as<Ramp>();
499 const Ramp *m2_ramp = m2_load->index.as<Ramp>();
500 internal_assert(m1_ramp && m2_ramp);
501 return can_prove(m1_ramp->base < m2_ramp->base);
502 }
503 };
504 const Shuffle *first_shuffle = mpys[0].first.as<Shuffle>();
505 if (first_shuffle) {
506 for (MulExpr &m : mpys) {
507 const Shuffle *shuffle = m.first.as<Shuffle>();
508 if (!shuffle || !shuffle->is_slice()) {
509 return;
510 }
511 }
512 std::stable_sort(mpys.begin(), mpys.end(),
513 [](const MulExpr &m1, const MulExpr &m2) {
514 return m1.first.as<Shuffle>()->slice_begin() < m2.first.as<Shuffle>()->slice_begin();
515 });
516 return;
517 } else if (const Load *first_load = mpys[0].first.as<Load>()) {
518 const Ramp *first_ramp = first_load->index.as<Ramp>();
519 if (!first_ramp) {
520 return;
521 }
522 for (MulExpr &m : mpys) {
523 const Load *load = m.first.as<Load>();
524 if (!load ||
525 load->name != first_load->name ||
526 !load->index.as<Ramp>()) {
527 return;
528 }
529 }
530 std::stable_sort(mpys.begin(), mpys.end(), LoadCompare());
531 }
532 }
533
534 // Look for adds in an Add expression. This is factored out of visit(const Add*) to
535 // enable look in widening_adds too.
536 Expr find_mpyadds(const Expr &op_add) {
537 const Add *op = op_add.as<Add>();
538 internal_assert(op);
539
540 // vmpa, vdmpy, and vrmpy instructions are hard to match with
541 // patterns, do it manually here.
542 // Try to find vrmpy opportunities first, which consume 4 operands.
543 if (op->type.is_vector() && (op->type.bits() == 16 || op->type.bits() == 32)) {
544 int lanes = op->type.lanes();
545 vector<MulExpr> mpys;
546 Expr rest;
547 string suffix;
548 int mpy_count = 0;
549
550 // Try to find a vector*scalar multiply first, which will
551 // match a subset of the expressions that vector*vector
552 // matches.
553 if (op->type.is_uint()) {
554 mpy_count = find_mpy_ops(op, UInt(8, lanes), UInt(8), 4, mpys, rest);
555 suffix = ".vub.ub";
556 } else {
557 mpy_count = find_mpy_ops(op, UInt(8, lanes), Int(8), 4, mpys, rest);
558 suffix = ".vub.b";
559 }
560
561 if (mpy_count > 0 && mpys.size() == 4) {
562 // It's possible that permuting the order of the
563 // multiply operands can simplify the shuffle away.
564 // So, give yourself a fighting chance by ordering the
565 // mpys in the ascending order of their start lanes (if all
566 // are slice_vectors) or in the ascending order of their
567 // load indices if all are loads from the same buffer.
568 sort_mpy_exprs(mpys);
569 Expr a0123 = Shuffle::make_interleave({mpys[0].first, mpys[1].first, mpys[2].first, mpys[3].first});
570 a0123 = simplify(a0123);
571
572 // We can generate this op for 16 bits, but, it's only
573 // faster to do so if the interleave simplifies away.
574 if (op->type.bits() == 32 || !a0123.as<Shuffle>()) {
575 Expr b0123 = Shuffle::make_interleave({mpys[0].second, mpys[1].second, mpys[2].second, mpys[3].second});
576 b0123 = simplify(b0123);
577 b0123 = reinterpret(Type(b0123.type().code(), 32, 1), b0123);
578 Expr new_expr = halide_hexagon_add_4mpy(op->type, suffix, a0123, b0123);
579 if (op->type.bits() == 16) {
580 // It's actually safe to use this op on 16 bit
581 // results, we just need to narrow the
582 // result. Overflow can occur, but will still
583 // produce the same result thanks to 2's
584 // complement arithmetic.
585 new_expr = Call::make(op->type, "halide.hexagon.pack.vw", {new_expr}, Call::PureExtern);
586 }
587 if (rest.defined()) {
588 new_expr = Add::make(new_expr, rest);
589 }
590 return mutate(new_expr);
591 }
592 }
593
594 // Now try to match vector*vector vrmpy expressions.
595 mpys.clear();
596 rest = Expr();
597 if (op->type.is_uint()) {
598 mpy_count = find_mpy_ops(op, UInt(8, lanes), UInt(8, lanes), 4, mpys, rest);
599 suffix = ".vub.vub";
600 } else {
601 mpy_count = find_mpy_ops(op, Int(8, lanes), Int(8, lanes), 4, mpys, rest);
602 suffix = ".vb.vb";
603 }
604
605 // TODO: suffix = ".vub.vb"
606 if (mpy_count > 0 && mpys.size() == 4) {
607 // It's possible that permuting the order of the
608 // multiply operands can simplify the shuffle away.
609 // So, give yourself a fighting chance by ordering the
610 // mpys in the ascending order of their start lanes (if all
611 // are slice_vectors) or in the ascending order of their
612 // load indices if all are loads from the same buffer.
613 sort_mpy_exprs(mpys);
614 Expr a0123 = Shuffle::make_interleave({mpys[0].first, mpys[1].first, mpys[2].first, mpys[3].first});
615 Expr b0123 = Shuffle::make_interleave({mpys[0].second, mpys[1].second, mpys[2].second, mpys[3].second});
616 a0123 = simplify(a0123);
617 b0123 = simplify(b0123);
618 // We can generate this op for 16 bits, but, it's only
619 // faster to do so if the interleave simplifies away.
620 if (op->type.bits() == 32 || (!a0123.as<Shuffle>() && !b0123.as<Shuffle>())) {
621 Expr new_expr = halide_hexagon_add_4mpy(op->type.with_bits(32), suffix, a0123, b0123);
622 if (op->type.bits() == 16) {
623 // It's actually safe to use this op on 16 bit
624 // results, we just need to narrow the
625 // result. Overflow can occur, but will still
626 // produce the same result thanks to 2's
627 // complement arithmetic.
628 new_expr = Call::make(op->type, "halide.hexagon.pack.vw", {new_expr}, Call::PureExtern);
629 }
630 if (rest.defined()) {
631 new_expr = Add::make(new_expr, rest);
632 }
633 return mutate(new_expr);
634 }
635 }
636 }
637
638 // Find opportunities vdmpy or vmpa.
639 if (op->type.is_vector() && (op->type.bits() == 16 || op->type.bits() == 32)) {
640 int lanes = op->type.lanes();
641
642 vector<MulExpr> mpys;
643 Expr rest;
644 string vmpa_suffix;
645 string vdmpy_suffix;
646 int mpy_count = 0;
647
648 // Try to find vector*scalar multiplies.
649 if (op->type.bits() == 16) {
650 mpy_count = find_mpy_ops(op, UInt(8, lanes), Int(8), 2, mpys, rest);
651 vmpa_suffix = ".vub.vub.b.b";
652 vdmpy_suffix = ".vub.b";
653 } else if (op->type.bits() == 32) {
654 mpy_count = find_mpy_ops(op, Int(16, lanes), Int(8), 2, mpys, rest);
655 vmpa_suffix = ".vh.vh.b.b";
656 vdmpy_suffix = ".vh.b";
657 }
658 if (mpy_count > 0 && mpys.size() == 2) {
659 // It's possible that permuting the order of the
660 // multiply operands can simplify the shuffle away.
661 // So, give yourself a fighting chance by ordering the
662 // mpys in the ascending order of their start lanes (if all
663 // are slice_vectors) or in the ascending order of their
664 // load indices if all are loads from the same buffer.
665 sort_mpy_exprs(mpys);
666 Expr a01 = Shuffle::make_interleave({mpys[0].first, mpys[1].first});
667 a01 = simplify(a01);
668 // TODO: This requires the operands to be in a
669 // particular order. It should be more robust... but
670 // this is pretty tough to do, other than simply
671 // trying all permutations.
672 Expr new_expr;
673 if (!a01.as<Shuffle>() || vmpa_suffix.empty()) {
674 Expr b01 = Shuffle::make_interleave({mpys[0].second, mpys[1].second, mpys[0].second, mpys[1].second});
675 b01 = simplify(b01);
676 b01 = reinterpret(Type(b01.type().code(), 32, 1), b01);
677 new_expr = halide_hexagon_add_2mpy(op->type, vdmpy_suffix, a01, b01);
678 } else {
679 new_expr = halide_hexagon_add_2mpy(op->type, vmpa_suffix, mpys[0].first, mpys[1].first, mpys[0].second, mpys[1].second);
680 }
681 if (rest.defined()) {
682 new_expr = Add::make(new_expr, rest);
683 }
684 return mutate(new_expr);
685 }
686 }
687 return Expr();
688 }

774 Expr visit(const Max *op) override {
775 Expr expr = IRMutator::visit(op);
776
777 if (op->type.is_vector()) {
778 // This pattern is weird (two operands must match, result
779 // needs 1 added) and we're unlikely to need another
780 // pattern for max, so just match it directly.
781 static const pair<string, Expr> cl[] = {
782 {"halide.hexagon.cls.vh", max(count_leading_zeros(wild_i16x), count_leading_zeros(~wild_i16x))},
783 {"halide.hexagon.cls.vw", max(count_leading_zeros(wild_i32x), count_leading_zeros(~wild_i32x))},
784 };
785 vector<Expr> matches;
786 for (const auto &i : cl) {
787 if (expr_match(i.second, expr, matches) && equal(matches[0], matches[1])) {
788 return Call::make(op->type, i.first, {matches[0]}, Call::PureExtern) + 1;
789 }
790 }
791 }
792 return expr;
793 }

871 // as two stage casts. This also avoids letting vector casts

873 // shuffles.

875 // Saturating narrowing
876 {u8_sat(wild_u32x), u8_sat(u16_sat(wild_u32x))},
877 {u8_sat(wild_i32x), u8_sat(i16_sat(wild_i32x))},

879 {i8_sat(wild_i32x), i8_sat(i16_sat(wild_i32x))},

882 {u8(wild_u32x), u8(u16(wild_u32x))},
883 {u8(wild_i32x), u8(i16(wild_i32x))},
884 {i8(wild_u32x), i8(u16(wild_u32x))},
885 {i8(wild_i32x), i8(i16(wild_i32x))},

891 {i32(wild_i8x), i32(i16(wild_i8x))},
892 };

897 Expr new_expr = apply_patterns(cast, casts, target, this);
898 if (!new_expr.same_as(cast)) {
899 return new_expr;
900 }

902 // If we didn't find a pattern, try using one of the
903 // rewrites above.
904 vector<Expr> matches;
905 for (const auto &i : cast_rewrites) {
906 if (expr_match(i.first, cast, matches)) {
907 Expr replacement = substitute("*", matches[0], with_lanes(i.second, op->type.lanes()));
908 debug(3) << "rewriting cast to: " << replacement << " from " << cast << "\n";
909 return mutate(replacement);
910 }
911 }
912 }
913 return IRMutator::visit(op);

919 if (mpyadds.defined()) {

924 // These intrinsics should get the default lowering, and we need to recursively mutate the
925 // result. We don't want to let these fall through to CodeGen_Hexagon and CodeGen_LLVM,

962 {"halide.hexagon.add_vuw.vuh.vuh", widening_add(wild_u16x, wild_u16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
963 {"halide.hexagon.add_vw.vh.vh", widening_add(wild_i16x, wild_i16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
964 {"halide.hexagon.sub_vh.vub.vub", widening_sub(wild_u8x, wild_u8x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
965 {"halide.hexagon.sub_vw.vuh.vuh", widening_sub(wild_u16x, wild_u16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
966 {"halide.hexagon.sub_vw.vh.vh", widening_sub(wild_i16x, wild_i16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
967 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vub.vub", widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_u8x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
968 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vub.vb", widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_i8x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
969 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vub.vb", widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Pattern::InterleaveResult | Pattern::SwapOps01},
970 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vb.vb", widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_i8x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
971 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vuh.vuh", widening_mul(wild_u16x, wild_u16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
972 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vh.vh", widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_i16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
973 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vh.vuh", widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_u16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult},
974 {"halide.hexagon.mpy.vh.vuh", widening_mul(wild_u16x, wild_i16x), Pattern::InterleaveResult | Pattern::SwapOps01},
975 };
976
977 if (op->type.is_vector()) {
978 Expr new_expr = apply_patterns(op, calls, target, this);
979 if (!new_expr.same_as(op)) {
980 return new_expr;
981 }
982 }
983
984 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::lerp)) {
985 // We need to lower lerps now to optimize the arithmetic
986 // that they generate.
987 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
988 return mutate(lower_lerp(op->args[0], op->args[1], op->args[2]));
989 } else if ((op->is_intrinsic(Call::div_round_to_zero) ||
990 op->is_intrinsic(Call::mod_round_to_zero)) &&
991 !op->type.is_float() && op->type.is_vector()) {
992 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
993 Expr a = op->args[0];
994 Expr b = op->args[1];
995 // Run bounds analysis to estimate the range of result.
996 Expr abs_result = op->type.is_int() ? abs(a / b) : a / b;
997 Expr extent_upper = find_constant_bound(abs_result, Direction::Upper, bounds);
998 const uint64_t *upper_bound = as_const_uint(extent_upper);
999 a = mutate(a);
1000 b = mutate(b);
1001 std::pair<Expr, Expr> div_mod = long_div_mod_round_to_zero(a, b, upper_bound);
1002 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::div_round_to_zero)) {
1003 return div_mod.first;
1004 }
1005 return div_mod.second;
1006 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::mul_shift_right) ||
1007 op->is_intrinsic(Call::rounding_mul_shift_right)) {
1008 // Lower these now, we might be able to use other patterns on the result.
1009 return mutate(lower_intrinsic(op));
1010 } else {
1011 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1012 }
1013 }
1014
1015 template<typename NodeType, typename T>
1016 NodeType visit_let(const T *op) {
1017 bounds.push(op->name, bounds_of_expr_in_scope(op->value, bounds));
1018 NodeType node = IRMutator::visit(op);
1019 bounds.pop(op->name);
1020 return node;
1021 }
1022
1023 Expr visit(const Let *op) override {
1024 return visit_let<Expr>(op);
1025 }
1026
1027 Stmt visit(const LetStmt *op) override {
1028 return visit_let<Stmt>(op);
1029 }
1030
1031 Expr visit(const Div *op) override {
1032 if (!op->type.is_float() && op->type.is_vector()) {
1033 return mutate(lower_int_uint_div(op->a, op->b));
1034 }
1035 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1036 }
1037
1038 Expr visit(const Mod *op) override {
1039 if (!op->type.is_float() && op->type.is_vector()) {
1040 return mutate(lower_int_uint_mod(op->a, op->b));
1041 }
1042 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1043 }
1044
1045public:
1046 OptimizePatterns(const Target &t)
1047 : target(t) {
1048 }
1049};

1051class VectorReducePatterns : public IRMutator {
1052 using IRMutator::visit;
1053
1054 // Check for interleaves of vectors with stride 1 like shuffle with indices:
1055 // 0, 1, 2,..., window_size - 1,
1056 // 1, 2, 3,..., window_size,
1057 // 2, 3, 4,..., window_size + 1,
1058 // .....
1059 // window_size != lanes
1060 // TODO: Their could be other patterns as well which we should match
1061 static int is_stencil_interleave(const Expr &op, int window_size) {
1062 int lanes = op.type().lanes();
1063 internal_assert(lanes > window_size);
1064 if (const Shuffle *shuff = op.as<Shuffle>()) {
1065 for (int i = window_size; i < lanes; i++) {
1066 if ((i % window_size != window_size - 1) &&
1067 (shuff->indices[i - window_size + 1] != shuff->indices[i])) {
1068 return false;
1069 }
1070 }
1071 return true;
1072 }
1073 return false;
1074 }
1075
1076 Expr visit(const VectorReduce *op) override {
1077 if (!op->type.is_vector() || op->type.is_float() || op->op != VectorReduce::Add) {
1078 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1079 }
1080
1081 struct Signature {
1082 enum Flags {
1083 SlidingWindow = 1,
1084 ScalarB = 1 << 1,
1085 NarrowB = 1 << 2,
1086 SwapOps = 1 << 3, // Swapping ops is done before matching B to scalars.
1087 };
1088 int factor;
1089 int native_return_bits;
1090 Expr pattern;
1091 int flags;
1092 };
1093
1094 int in_lanes = op->value.type().lanes();
1095 int out_lanes = op->type.lanes();
1096 int factor = in_lanes / out_lanes;
1097
1098 // Map of instruction signatures
1099 // clang-format off
1100 static const vector<Signature> sigs = {
1101 // --------- vrmpy ---------
1102 // Sliding window
1103 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_u8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB},
1104 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_i8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB},
1105 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB | Signature::SwapOps},
1106 // Vector * Scalar
1107 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_u8x), Signature::ScalarB},
1108 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Signature::ScalarB},
1109 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_i8x), Signature::ScalarB},
1110 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Signature::ScalarB | Signature::SwapOps},
1111 // Vector * Vector
1112 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_u8x)},
1113 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_i8x)},
1114 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Signature::SwapOps},
1115 {4, 32, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_i8x)},
1116 // Sum
1117 {4, 32, wild_u8x, Signature::SlidingWindow},
1118 {4, 32, wild_i8x, Signature::SlidingWindow},
1119 {4, 32, wild_u8x},
1120 {4, 32, wild_i8x},
1121
1122 // --------- vtmpy ---------
1123 // Vtmpy has additional requirement that third coefficient b[2]
1124 // needs to be 1.
1125 // Sliding window
1126 {3, 16, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_i8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB},
1127 {3, 16, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_i8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB},
1128 {3, 16, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB | Signature::SwapOps},
1129 {3, 32, widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_i16x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB},
1130 // Sum
1131 {3, 16, wild_i8x, Signature::SlidingWindow},
1132 {3, 16, wild_u8x, Signature::SlidingWindow},
1133 {3, 32, wild_i16x, Signature::SlidingWindow},
1134
1135 // --------- vdmpy ---------
1136 // Sliding window
1137 {2, 16, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_i8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB},
1138 {2, 16, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB | Signature::SwapOps},
1139 {2, 32, widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_i16x), Signature::SlidingWindow | Signature::ScalarB},
1140 // Vector * Scalar
1141 {2, 16, widening_mul(wild_u8x, wild_i8x), Signature::ScalarB},
1142 {2, 16, widening_mul(wild_i8x, wild_u8x), Signature::ScalarB | Signature::SwapOps},
1143 {2, 32, widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_i16x), Signature::ScalarB | Signature::NarrowB},
1144 {2, 32, widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_u16x), Signature::ScalarB}, // Saturates
1145 {2, 32, widening_mul(wild_u16x, wild_i16x), Signature::ScalarB | Signature::SwapOps}, // Saturates
1146 {2, 32, widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_i16x), Signature::ScalarB}, // Saturates
1147 // Vector * Vector
1148 {2, 32, widening_mul(wild_i16x, wild_i16x)}, // Saturates
1149 // Sum
1150 {2, 16, wild_u8x, Signature::SlidingWindow},
1151 {2, 32, wild_i16x, Signature::SlidingWindow},
1152 {2, 16, wild_u8x},
1153 {2, 32, wild_i16x},
1154 };
1155 // clang-format on
1156 std::vector<Expr> matches;
1157 for (const Signature &sig : sigs) {
1158 if (factor != sig.factor) {
1159 continue;
1160 }
1161 // Try matching the pattern with any number of bits between the pattern type and the native result.
1162 for (int bits = sig.pattern.type().bits(); bits <= sig.native_return_bits; bits *= 2) {
1163 matches.clear();
1164 Expr pattern = sig.pattern;
1165 if (bits != pattern.type().bits()) {
1166 // Allow the widening cast to cast to the type of the result, which may
1167 // differ from the pattern.
1168 pattern = Cast::make(op->type.with_bits(bits).with_lanes(0), pattern);
1169 }
1170 if (expr_match(pattern, op->value, matches)) {
1171 break;
1172 }
1173 }
1174 if (matches.empty()) {
1175 continue;
1176 }
1177
1178 Expr a = matches[0];
1179 Expr b = matches.size() > 1 ? matches[1] : make_const(Type(op->type.code(), 8, factor), 1);
1180 if (sig.flags & Signature::SwapOps) {
1181 std::swap(a, b);
1182 }
1183
1184 if (sig.flags & Signature::ScalarB) {
1185 if (const Shuffle *shuff = b.as<Shuffle>()) {
1186 if (shuff->is_broadcast() && shuff->broadcast_factor() % factor == 0) {
1187 internal_assert(shuff->vectors.size() == 1);
1188 b = Shuffle::make_slice(shuff->vectors[0], 0, 1, factor);
1189 }
1190 } else if (const Shuffle *shuff = a.as<Shuffle>()) {
1191 // If the types are equal, we can commute the ops.
1192 if (a.type().element_of() == b.type().element_of() &&
1193 shuff->is_broadcast() && shuff->broadcast_factor() % factor == 0) {
1194 internal_assert(shuff->vectors.size() == 1);
1195 a = Shuffle::make_slice(shuff->vectors[0], 0, 1, factor);
1196 std::swap(a, b);
1197 }
1198 }
1199 if (b.type().lanes() != factor) {
1200 // This isn't a scalar, it doesn't match the pattern.
1201 continue;
1202 }
1203 }
1204
1205 if (sig.flags & Signature::NarrowB) {
1206 b = lossless_cast(b.type().narrow(), b);
1207 if (!b.defined()) {
1208 continue;
1209 }
1210 }
1211
1212 Expr a0, a1;
1213 if (sig.flags & Signature::SlidingWindow) {
1214 if (!is_stencil_interleave(a, factor)) {
1215 continue;
1216 }
1217 // Split a into a0, a1 to get the correct vector args
1218 // for sliding window reduction instructions. Below are
1219 // required shuffle indices for a0 and a1:
1220 // For factor == 2:
1221 // If a -> shuff[0, 1,...., out_lanes]
1222 // a0 -> shuff[0, 1,...., out_lanes - 1]
1223 // a1 -> shuff[2, 3,...., out_lanes + 1]
1224 // Last index of a1 is don't care
1225 // For factor == 3:
1226 // If a -> shuff[0, 1,...., out_lanes + 1]
1227 // a0 -> shuff[0, 1,...., out_lanes - 1]
1228 // a1 -> shuff[2, 3,...., out_lanes + 1]
1229 // For factor == 4:
1230 // If a -> shuff[0, 1,...., out_lanes + 3]
1231 // a0 -> shuff[0, 1,...., out_lanes - 1]
1232 // a1 -> shuff[4, 5,...., out_lanes + 4]
1233 // Last index of a1 is don't care
1234 // TODO: Why does this require a to be a shuffle? Why isn't this just:
1235 // a0 = Shuffle::make_slice(a, 0, factor, out_lanes);
1236 // a1 = Shuffle::make_slice(a, factor - 1, factor, out_lanes);
1237 // The current code probably also generates messier shuffles the backend
1238 // may not recognize.
1239 if (const Shuffle *shuff = a.as<Shuffle>()) {
1240 vector<int> a0_indices(out_lanes), a1_indices(out_lanes);
1241 for (int i = 0; i < out_lanes; i++) {
1242 a0_indices[i] = shuff->indices[i * factor];
1243 a1_indices[i] = shuff->indices[(i + 1) * factor - 1];
1244 }
1245 a0 = Shuffle::make(shuff->vectors, a0_indices);
1246 a1 = Shuffle::make(shuff->vectors, a1_indices);
1247 if (factor == 2 || factor == 4) {
1248 // We'll need to rotate the indices by one element
1249 // to get the correct order.
1250 Type ty = UInt(8).with_lanes(a1.type().lanes() * a1.type().bytes());
1251 a1 = reinterpret(a1.type(),
1252 Call::make(ty, "halide.hexagon.vror",
1253 {reinterpret(ty, a1), a1.type().bytes()},
1254 Call::PureExtern));
1255 } else {
1256 // Vtmpy has additional requirement that third
1257 // coefficient b[2] needs to be 1.
1258 if (!can_prove(Shuffle::make_extract_element(b, 2) == 1)) {
1259 continue;
1260 }
1261 b = Shuffle::make_slice(b, 0, 1, 2);
1262 }
1263 a = Shuffle::make_concat({a0, a1});
1264 } else {
1265 continue;
1266 }
1267 }
1268
1269 std::string suffix = type_suffix(a);
1270 if (b.type().lanes() <= factor) {
1271 suffix += type_suffix(b.type().element_of());
1272 if (b.type().lanes() * b.type().bits() <= 16) {
1273 b = Shuffle::make({b}, {0, 1, 0, 1});
1274 }
1275 // Reinterpret scalar b arg to get correct type.
1276 b = simplify(reinterpret(Type(b.type().code(), b.type().lanes() * b.type().bits(), 1), b));
1277 } else {
1278 suffix += type_suffix(b);
1279 }
1280
1281 Type result_type = op->type.with_bits(sig.native_return_bits);
1282
1283 Expr result;
1284 if (factor == 4) {
1285 if (sig.flags & Signature::SlidingWindow) {
1286 result = halide_hexagon_add_4mpy(result_type, suffix + ".stencil", a, b);
1287 } else {
1288 result = halide_hexagon_add_4mpy(result_type, suffix, a, b);
1289 }
1290 } else {
1291 if (sig.flags & Signature::SlidingWindow) {
1292 string name = "halide.hexagon.add_" + std::to_string(factor) + "mpy" + suffix;
1293 result = native_interleave(Call::make(result_type, name, {a, b}, Call::PureExtern));
1294 } else {
1295 // factor == 3 has only sliding window reductions.
1296 result = halide_hexagon_add_2mpy(result_type, suffix, a, b);
1297 }
1298 }
1299 if (result.type() != op->type) {
1300 result = Cast::make(op->type, result);
1301 }
1302 return result;
1303 }
1304 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1305 }
1306};
1307
1308// Attempt to cancel out redundant interleave/deinterleave pairs. The
1309// basic strategy is to push interleavings toward the end of the
1310// program, using the fact that interleaves can pass through pointwise
1311// IR operations. When an interleave collides with a deinterleave,
1312// they cancel out.
1313class EliminateInterleaves : public IRMutator {
1314 Scope<bool> vars;
1315
1316 // We need to know when loads are a multiple of 2 native vectors.
1317 int native_vector_bits;
1318
1319 // Alignment analyzer for loads and stores
1320 HexagonAlignmentAnalyzer alignment_analyzer;
1321
1322 // Check if x is an expression that is either an interleave, or
1323 // transitively is an interleave.
1324 bool yields_removable_interleave(const Expr &x) {
1325 if (is_native_interleave(x)) {
1326 return true;
1327 }
1328
1329 if (const Let *let = x.as<Let>()) {
1330 return yields_removable_interleave(let->body);
1331 }
1332
1333 const Variable *var = x.as<Variable>();
1334 if (var && vars.contains(var->name + ".deinterleaved")) {
1335 return true;
1336 }
1337
1338 if (const Load *load = x.as<Load>()) {
1339 if (buffers.contains(load->name)) {
1340 return buffers.get(load->name) != BufferState::NotInterleaved;
1341 }
1342 }
1343
1344 if (const Add *op = x.as<Add>()) {
1345 return yields_removable_interleave(op->a) || yields_removable_interleave(op->b);
1346 } else if (const Sub *op = x.as<Sub>()) {
1347 return yields_removable_interleave(op->a) || yields_removable_interleave(op->b);
1348 }
1349
1350 return false;
1351 }
1352
1353 // Check if x either has a removable interleave, or it can pretend
1354 // to be an interleave at no cost (a scalar or a broadcast).
1355 bool yields_interleave(const Expr &x) {
1356 if (yields_removable_interleave(x)) {
1357 return true;
1358 }
1359
1360 // These yield an interleave, but we shouldn't
1361 // deinterleave them if we want to remove an actual
1362 // interleave.
1363 if (x.type().is_scalar() || x.as<Broadcast>()) {
1364 return true;
1365 }
1366
1367 if (const Let *let = x.as<Let>()) {
1368 return yields_interleave(let->body);
1369 }
1370
1371 // This is different from the deinterleaved lets handled in
1372 // yields_removable_interleave. These are lets that can be
1373 // deinterleaved freely, but are not actually interleaves.
1374 const Variable *var = x.as<Variable>();
1375 if (var && vars.contains(var->name + ".weak_deinterleaved")) {
1376 return true;
1377 }
1378
1379 if (const Load *load = x.as<Load>()) {
1380 if (buffers.contains(load->name)) {
1381 return buffers.get(load->name) != BufferState::NotInterleaved;
1382 }
1383 }
1384
1385 if (const Add *op = x.as<Add>()) {
1386 return yields_interleave(op->a) || yields_interleave(op->b);
1387 } else if (const Sub *op = x.as<Sub>()) {
1388 return yields_interleave(op->a) || yields_interleave(op->b);
1389 }
1390
1391 return false;
1392 }
1393
1394 // Check that if we were to remove interleaves from exprs, that
1395 // we would remove more interleaves than we added deinterleaves.
1396 bool yields_removable_interleave(const vector<Expr> &exprs) {
1397 int removable = 0;
1398 int does_not_yield = 0;
1399 for (const Expr &i : exprs) {
1400 if (yields_removable_interleave(i)) {
1401 removable++;
1402 } else if (!yields_interleave(i)) {
1403 does_not_yield++;
1404 }
1405 }
1406 return removable > 0 && removable >= does_not_yield;
1407 }
1408
1409 // Asserting that x is an expression that can yield an interleave
1410 // operation, return the expression being interleaved.
1411 Expr remove_interleave(Expr x) {
1412 if (is_native_interleave(x)) {
1413 return x.as<Call>()->args[0];
1414 } else if (x.type().is_scalar() || x.as<Broadcast>()) {
1415 return x;
1416 }
1417
1418 if (const Variable *var = x.as<Variable>()) {
1419 if (vars.contains(var->name + ".deinterleaved")) {
1420 return Variable::make(var->type, var->name + ".deinterleaved");
1421 } else if (vars.contains(var->name + ".weak_deinterleaved")) {
1422 return Variable::make(var->type, var->name + ".weak_deinterleaved");
1423 }
1424 }
1425
1426 if (const Let *let = x.as<Let>()) {
1427 Expr body = remove_interleave(let->body);
1428 if (!body.same_as(let->body)) {
1429 return Let::make(let->name, let->value, body);
1430 } else {
1431 return x;
1432 }
1433 }
1434
1435 if (const Load *load = x.as<Load>()) {
1436 if (buffers.contains(load->name)) {
1437 BufferState &state = buffers.ref(load->name);
1438 if (state != BufferState::NotInterleaved) {
1439 state = BufferState::Interleaved;
1440 return x;
1441 }
1442 }
1443 }
1444
1445 if (const Add *op = x.as<Add>()) {
1446 return Add::make(remove_interleave(op->a), remove_interleave(op->b));
1447 } else if (const Sub *op = x.as<Sub>()) {
1448 return Sub::make(remove_interleave(op->a), remove_interleave(op->b));
1449 }
1450
1451 // If we rewrite x as interleave(deinterleave(x)), we can remove the interleave.
1452 return native_deinterleave(x);
1453 }
1454
1455 template<typename T>
1456 Expr visit_binary(const T *op) {
1457 Expr expr;
1458 Expr a = mutate(op->a);
1459 Expr b = mutate(op->b);
1460 if (yields_removable_interleave({a, b})) {
1461 expr = T::make(remove_interleave(a), remove_interleave(b));
1462 expr = native_interleave(expr);
1463 } else if (!a.same_as(op->a) || !b.same_as(op->b)) {
1464 expr = T::make(a, b);
1465 } else {
1466 expr = op;
1467 }
1468 return expr;
1469 }
1470
1471 Expr visit(const Add *op) override {
1472 return visit_binary(op);
1473 }
1474 Expr visit(const Sub *op) override {
1475 return visit_binary(op);
1476 }
1477 Expr visit(const Mul *op) override {
1478 return visit_binary(op);
1479 }
1480 Expr visit(const Div *op) override {
1481 return visit_binary(op);
1482 }
1483 Expr visit(const Mod *op) override {
1484 return visit_binary(op);
1485 }
1486 Expr visit(const Min *op) override {
1487 return visit_binary(op);
1488 }
1489 Expr visit(const Max *op) override {
1490 return visit_binary(op);
1491 }
1492
1493 Expr visit(const Select *op) override {
1494 Expr true_value = mutate(op->true_value);
1495 Expr false_value = mutate(op->false_value);
1496 Expr cond = mutate(op->condition);
1497
1498 // The condition isn't a vector, so we can just check if we
1499 // should move an interleave from the true/false values.
1500 if (cond.type().is_scalar() && yields_removable_interleave({true_value, false_value})) {
1501 true_value = remove_interleave(true_value);
1502 false_value = remove_interleave(false_value);
1503 return native_interleave(Select::make(cond, true_value, false_value));
1504 } else if (!cond.same_as(op->condition) ||
1505 !true_value.same_as(op->true_value) ||
1506 !false_value.same_as(op->false_value)) {
1507 return Select::make(cond, true_value, false_value);
1508 } else {
1509 return op;
1510 }
1511 }
1512
1513 template<typename NodeType, typename LetType>
1514 NodeType visit_let(const LetType *op) {
1515
1516 Expr value = mutate(op->value);
1517 string deinterleaved_name;
1518 NodeType body;
1519 // Other code in this mutator needs to be able to tell the
1520 // difference between a Let that yields a deinterleave, and a
1521 // let that has a removable deinterleave. Lets that can
1522 // pretend to be deinterleaved at no cost are given an
1523 // alternative let labelled "weak_deinterleaved", while lets
1524 // that have a removable interleave are given an alternative
1525 // let labelled "deinterleaved".
1526 if (yields_removable_interleave(value)) {
1527 // We can provide a deinterleaved version of this let value.
1528 deinterleaved_name = op->name + ".deinterleaved";
1529 vars.push(deinterleaved_name, true);
1530 body = mutate(op->body);
1531 vars.pop(deinterleaved_name);
1532 } else if (yields_interleave(value)) {
1533 // We have a soft deinterleaved version of this let value.
1534 deinterleaved_name = op->name + ".weak_deinterleaved";
1535 vars.push(deinterleaved_name, true);
1536 body = mutate(op->body);
1537 vars.pop(deinterleaved_name);
1538 } else {
1539 body = mutate(op->body);
1540 }
1541
1542 if (value.same_as(op->value) && body.same_as(op->body)) {
1543 return op;
1544 } else if (body.same_as(op->body)) {
1545 // If the body didn't change, we must not have used the deinterleaved value.
1546 return LetType::make(op->name, value, body);
1547 } else {
1548 // We need to rewrap the body with new lets.
1549 NodeType result = body;
1550 bool deinterleaved_used = stmt_or_expr_uses_var(result, deinterleaved_name);
1551 bool interleaved_used = stmt_or_expr_uses_var(result, op->name);
1552 if (deinterleaved_used && interleaved_used) {
1553 // The body uses both the interleaved and
1554 // deinterleaved version of this let. Generate both
1555 // lets, using the deinterleaved one to generate the
1556 // interleaved one.
1557 Expr deinterleaved = remove_interleave(value);
1558
1559 // If we actually removed an interleave from the
1560 // value, re-interleave it to get the interleaved let
1561 // value.
1562 Expr interleaved = Variable::make(deinterleaved.type(), deinterleaved_name);
1563 if (!deinterleaved.same_as(value)) {
1564 interleaved = native_interleave(interleaved);
1565 }
1566
1567 result = LetType::make(op->name, interleaved, result);
1568 return LetType::make(deinterleaved_name, deinterleaved, result);
1569 } else if (deinterleaved_used) {
1570 // Only the deinterleaved value is used, we can eliminate the interleave.
1571 return LetType::make(deinterleaved_name, remove_interleave(value), result);
1572 } else if (interleaved_used) {
1573 // Only the original value is used, regenerate the let.
1574 return LetType::make(op->name, value, result);
1575 } else {
1576 // The let must have been dead.
1577 internal_assert(!stmt_or_expr_uses_var(op->body, op->name))
1578 << "EliminateInterleaves eliminated a non-dead let.\n";
1579 return op->body;
1580 }
1581 }
1582 }
1583
1584 Expr visit(const Let *op) override {
1585 Expr expr = visit_let<Expr>(op);
1586
1587 // Lift interleaves out of Let expression bodies.
1588 const Let *let = expr.as<Let>();
1589 if (let && yields_removable_interleave(let->body)) {
1590 expr = native_interleave(Let::make(let->name, let->value, remove_interleave(let->body)));
1591 }
1592 return expr;
1593 }
1594
1595 Stmt visit(const LetStmt *op) override {
1596 return visit_let<Stmt>(op);
1597 }
1598
1599 Expr visit(const Cast *op) override {
1600 if (op->type.bits() == op->value.type().bits()) {
1601 // We can only move interleaves through casts of the same size.
1602 Expr value = mutate(op->value);
1603
1604 if (yields_removable_interleave(value)) {
1605 value = remove_interleave(value);
1606 return native_interleave(Cast::make(op->type, value));
1607 } else if (!value.same_as(op->value)) {
1608 return Cast::make(op->type, value);
1609 } else {
1610 return op;
1611 }
1612 } else {
1613 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1614 }
1615 }
1616
1617 static bool is_interleavable(const Call *op) {
1618 // These calls can have interleaves moved from operands to the
1619 // result...
1620 static const set<string> interleavable = {
1621 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::bitwise_and),
1622 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::bitwise_not),
1623 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::bitwise_xor),
1624 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::bitwise_or),
1625 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::shift_left),
1626 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::shift_right),
1627 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::abs),
1628 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::absd)};
1629 if (interleavable.count(op->name) != 0) {
1630 return true;
1631 }
1632
1633 // ...these calls cannot. Furthermore, these calls have the
1634 // same return type as the arguments, which means our test
1635 // below will be inaccurate.
1636 static const set<string> not_interleavable = {
1637 "halide.hexagon.interleave.vb",
1638 "halide.hexagon.interleave.vh",
1639 "halide.hexagon.interleave.vw",
1640 "halide.hexagon.deinterleave.vb",
1641 "halide.hexagon.deinterleave.vh",
1642 "halide.hexagon.deinterleave.vw",
1643 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::hvx_gather),
1644 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::hvx_scatter),
1645 Call::get_intrinsic_name(Call::hvx_scatter_acc),
1646 };
1647 if (not_interleavable.count(op->name) != 0) {
1648 return false;
1649 }
1650
1651 if (starts_with(op->name, "halide.hexagon.")) {
1652 // We assume that any hexagon intrinsic is interleavable
1653 // as long as all of the vector operands have the same
1654 // number of lanes and lane width as the return type.
1655 for (const Expr &i : op->args) {
1656 if (i.type().is_scalar()) {
1657 continue;
1658 }
1659 if (i.type().bits() != op->type.bits() || i.type().lanes() != op->type.lanes()) {
1660 return false;
1661 }
1662 }
1663 }
1664 return true;
1665 }
1666
1667 Expr visit(const Call *op) override {
1668 vector<Expr> args(op->args);
1669
1670 // mutate all the args.
1671 bool changed = false;
1672 for (Expr &i : args) {
1673 Expr new_i = mutate(i);
1674 changed = changed || !new_i.same_as(i);
1675 i = new_i;
1676 }
1677
1678 // For a few operations, we have a choice of several
1679 // instructions, an interleaving or a non-inerleaving
1680 // variant. We handle this by generating the instruction that
1681 // does not deinterleave, and then opportunistically select
1682 // the interleaving alternative when we can cancel out to the
1683 // interleave.
1684 static std::map<string, string> deinterleaving_alts = {
1685 {"halide.hexagon.pack.vh", "halide.hexagon.trunc.vh"},
1686 {"halide.hexagon.pack.vw", "halide.hexagon.trunc.vw"},
1687 {"halide.hexagon.packhi.vh", "halide.hexagon.trunclo.vh"},
1688 {"halide.hexagon.packhi.vw", "halide.hexagon.trunclo.vw"},
1689 {"halide.hexagon.pack_satub.vh", "halide.hexagon.trunc_satub.vh"},
1690 {"halide.hexagon.pack_sath.vw", "halide.hexagon.trunc_sath.vw"},
1691 {"halide.hexagon.pack_satuh.vw", "halide.hexagon.trunc_satuh.vw"},
1692 };
1693
1694 // The reverse mapping of the above.
1695 static std::map<string, string> interleaving_alts = {
1696 {"halide.hexagon.trunc.vh", "halide.hexagon.pack.vh"},
1697 {"halide.hexagon.trunc.vw", "halide.hexagon.pack.vw"},
1698 {"halide.hexagon.trunclo.vh", "halide.hexagon.packhi.vh"},
1699 {"halide.hexagon.trunclo.vw", "halide.hexagon.packhi.vw"},
1700 {"halide.hexagon.trunc_satub.vh", "halide.hexagon.pack_satub.vh"},
1701 {"halide.hexagon.trunc_sath.vw", "halide.hexagon.pack_sath.vw"},
1702 {"halide.hexagon.trunc_satuh.vw", "halide.hexagon.pack_satuh.vw"},
1703 };
1704
1705 if (is_native_deinterleave(op) && yields_interleave(args[0])) {
1706 // This is a deinterleave of an interleave! Remove them both.
1707 return remove_interleave(args[0]);
1708 } else if (is_interleavable(op) && yields_removable_interleave(args)) {
1709 // We can reduce the total number of interleave and deinterleave
1710 // operations by removing interleaves from the arguments.
1711 for (Expr &i : args) {
1712 i = remove_interleave(i);
1713 }
1714 Expr expr = Call::make(op->type, op->name, args, op->call_type,
1715 op->func, op->value_index, op->image, op->param);
1716 // Add the interleave back to the result of the call.
1717 return native_interleave(expr);
1718 } else if (deinterleaving_alts.find(op->name) != deinterleaving_alts.end() &&
1719 yields_removable_interleave(args)) {
1720 // This call has a deinterleaving alternative, and the
1721 // arguments are interleaved, so we should use the
1722 // alternative instead.
1723 for (Expr &i : args) {
1724 i = remove_interleave(i);
1725 }
1726 return Call::make(op->type, deinterleaving_alts[op->name], args, op->call_type);
1727 } else if (interleaving_alts.count(op->name) && is_native_deinterleave(args[0])) {
1728 // This is an interleaving alternative with a
1729 // deinterleave, which can be generated when we
1730 // deinterleave storage. Revert back to the interleaving
1731 // op so we can remove the deinterleave.
1732 Expr arg = args[0].as<Call>()->args[0];
1733 return Call::make(op->type, interleaving_alts[op->name], {arg}, op->call_type,
1734 op->func, op->value_index, op->image, op->param);
1735 } else if (changed) {
1736 return Call::make(op->type, op->name, args, op->call_type,
1737 op->func, op->value_index, op->image, op->param);
1738 } else {
1739 return op;
1740 }
1741 }
1742
1743 // Track whether buffers are interleaved or not.
1744 enum class BufferState {
1745 Unknown, // We don't know if this buffer is interleaved or not.
1746 Interleaved, // We know the buffer is interleaved.
1747 NotInterleaved, // We know the buffer is not interleaved.
1748 };
1749 Scope<BufferState> buffers;
1750
1751 // False for buffers that have any loads or stores that are unaligned
1752 Scope<bool> aligned_buffer_access;
1753
1754 // Buffers we should deinterleave the storage of.
1755 Scope<bool> deinterleave_buffers;
1756
1757 Stmt visit(const Allocate *op) override {
1758 Expr condition = mutate(op->condition);
1759
1760 // First, we need to mutate the op, to pull native interleaves
1761 // down, and to gather information about the loads and stores.
1762 buffers.push(op->name, BufferState::Unknown);
1763
1764 // Assume buffers are accessed by aligned loads and stores by default.
1765 aligned_buffer_access.push(op->name, true);
1766
1767 Stmt body = mutate(op->body);
1768 bool deinterleave = (buffers.get(op->name) == BufferState::Interleaved) &&
1769 (aligned_buffer_access.get(op->name) == true);
1770 buffers.pop(op->name);
1771
1772 // Second, if we decided it would be useful to deinterleave
1773 // the storage of this buffer, do so now.
1774 if (deinterleave) {
1775 deinterleave_buffers.push(op->name, true);
1776 body = mutate(op->body);
1777 deinterleave_buffers.pop(op->name);
1778 }
1779
1780 aligned_buffer_access.pop(op->name);
1781
1782 if (!body.same_as(op->body) || !condition.same_as(op->condition)) {
1783 return Allocate::make(op->name, op->type, op->memory_type,
1784 op->extents, condition, body,
1785 op->new_expr, op->free_function);
1786 } else {
1787 return op;
1788 }
1789 }
1790
1791 Stmt visit(const Store *op) override {
1792 Expr predicate = mutate(op->predicate);
1793 Expr value = mutate(op->value);
1794 Expr index = mutate(op->index);
1795
1796 if (buffers.contains(op->name)) {
1797 // When inspecting the stores to a buffer, update the state.
1798 BufferState &state = buffers.ref(op->name);
1799 if (!is_const_one(predicate) || !op->value.type().is_vector()) {
1800 // TODO(psuriana): This store is predicated. Mark the buffer as
1801 // not interleaved for now.
1802 state = BufferState::NotInterleaved;
1803 } else if (yields_removable_interleave(value)) {
1804 // The value yields a removable interleave. If we aren't tracking
1805 // this buffer, mark it as interleaved.
1806 if (state == BufferState::Unknown) {
1807 state = BufferState::Interleaved;
1808 }
1809 } else if (!yields_interleave(value)) {
1810 // The value does not yield an interleave. Mark the
1811 // buffer as not interleaved.
1812 state = BufferState::NotInterleaved;
1813 } else {
1814 // If the buffer yields an interleave, but is not an
1815 // interleave itself, we don't want to change the
1816 // buffer state.
1817 }
1818 internal_assert(aligned_buffer_access.contains(op->name) && "Buffer not found in scope");
1819 bool &aligned_accesses = aligned_buffer_access.ref(op->name);
1820 int64_t aligned_offset = 0;
1821
1822 if (!alignment_analyzer.is_aligned(op, &aligned_offset)) {
1823 aligned_accesses = false;
1824 }
1825 }
1826 if (deinterleave_buffers.contains(op->name)) {
1827 // We're deinterleaving this buffer, remove the interleave
1828 // from the store.
1829 internal_assert(is_const_one(predicate)) << "The store shouldn't have been predicated.\n";
1830 value = remove_interleave(value);
1831 }
1832
1833 if (predicate.same_as(op->predicate) && value.same_as(op->value) && index.same_as(op->index)) {
1834 return op;
1835 } else {
1836 return Store::make(op->name, value, index, op->param, predicate, op->alignment);
1837 }
1838 }
1839
1840 Expr visit(const Load *op) override {
1841 if (buffers.contains(op->name)) {
1842 if ((op->type.lanes() * op->type.bits()) % (native_vector_bits * 2) == 0) {
1843 // This is a double vector load, we might be able to
1844 // deinterleave the storage of this buffer.
1845 // We don't want to actually do anything to the buffer
1846 // state here. We know we can interleave the load if
1847 // necessary, but we don't want to cause it to be
1848 // interleaved unless it is a useful improvement,
1849 // which is only true if any of the stores are
1850 // actually interleaved (and don't just yield an
1851 // interleave).
1852 internal_assert(aligned_buffer_access.contains(op->name) && "Buffer not found in scope");
1853 bool &aligned_accesses = aligned_buffer_access.ref(op->name);
1854 int64_t aligned_offset = 0;
1855
1856 if (!alignment_analyzer.is_aligned(op, &aligned_offset)) {
1857 aligned_accesses = false;
1858 }
1859 } else {
1860 // This is not a double vector load, so we can't
1861 // deinterleave the storage of this buffer.
1862 BufferState &state = buffers.ref(op->name);
1863 state = BufferState::NotInterleaved;
1864 }
1865 }
1866 Expr expr = IRMutator::visit(op);
1867 if (deinterleave_buffers.contains(op->name)) {
1868 expr = native_interleave(expr);
1869 }
1870 return expr;
1871 }
1872
1873 using IRMutator::visit;
1874
1875public:
1876 EliminateInterleaves(int native_vector_bytes)
1877 : native_vector_bits(native_vector_bytes * 8), alignment_analyzer(native_vector_bytes) {
1878 }
1879};
1880
1881// After eliminating interleaves, there may be some that remain. This
1882// mutator attempts to replace interleaves paired with other
1883// operations that do not require an interleave. It's important to do
1884// this after all other efforts to eliminate the interleaves,
1885// otherwise this might eat some interleaves that could have cancelled
1886// with other operations.
1887class FuseInterleaves : public IRMutator {
1888 Expr visit(const Call *op) override {
1889 // This is a list of {f, g} pairs that if the first operation
1890 // is interleaved, interleave(f(x)) is equivalent to g(x).
1891 static const std::vector<std::pair<string, string>> non_deinterleaving_alts = {
1892 {"halide.hexagon.zxt.vub", "halide.hexagon.unpack.vub"},
1893 {"halide.hexagon.sxt.vb", "halide.hexagon.unpack.vb"},
1894 {"halide.hexagon.zxt.vuh", "halide.hexagon.unpack.vuh"},
1895 {"halide.hexagon.sxt.vh", "halide.hexagon.unpack.vh"},
1896 };
1897
1898 if (is_native_interleave(op)) {
1899 if (const Call *arg = op->args[0].as<Call>()) {
1900 for (const auto &i : non_deinterleaving_alts) {
1901 if (arg->name == i.first) {
1902 std::vector<Expr> args = arg->args;
1903 for (Expr &j : args) {
1904 j = mutate(j);
1905 }
1906 return Call::make(op->type, i.second, args, Call::PureExtern);
1907 }
1908 }
1909 }
1910 }
1911
1912 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1913 }
1914
1915 using IRMutator::visit;
1916};

1918// Find an upper bound of bounds.max - bounds.min.
1919Expr span_of_bounds(const Interval &bounds) {
1920 internal_assert(bounds.is_bounded());
1921
1922 const Min *min_min = bounds.min.as<Min>();
1923 const Max *min_max = bounds.min.as<Max>();
1924 const Min *max_min = bounds.max.as<Min>();
1925 const Max *max_max = bounds.max.as<Max>();
1926 const Add *min_add = bounds.min.as<Add>();
1927 const Add *max_add = bounds.max.as<Add>();
1928 const Sub *min_sub = bounds.min.as<Sub>();
1929 const Sub *max_sub = bounds.max.as<Sub>();
1930
1931 if (min_min && max_min && equal(min_min->b, max_min->b)) {
1932 return span_of_bounds({min_min->a, max_min->a});
1933 } else if (min_max && max_max && equal(min_max->b, max_max->b)) {
1934 return span_of_bounds({min_max->a, max_max->a});
1935 } else if (min_add && max_add && equal(min_add->b, max_add->b)) {
1936 return span_of_bounds({min_add->a, max_add->a});
1937 } else if (min_sub && max_sub && equal(min_sub->b, max_sub->b)) {
1938 return span_of_bounds({min_sub->a, max_sub->a});
1939 } else {
1940 return bounds.max - bounds.min;
1941 }
1942}

1944// Replace indirect loads with dynamic_shuffle intrinsics where
1945// possible.
1946class OptimizeShuffles : public IRMutator {
1947 int lut_alignment;
1948 Scope<Interval> bounds;
1949 std::vector<std::pair<string, Expr>> lets;
1950
1951 using IRMutator::visit;
1952
1953 template<typename NodeType, typename T>
1954 NodeType visit_let(const T *op) {
1955 // We only care about vector lets.
1956 if (op->value.type().is_vector()) {
1957 bounds.push(op->name, bounds_of_expr_in_scope(op->value, bounds));
1958 }
1959 NodeType node = IRMutator::visit(op);
1960 if (op->value.type().is_vector()) {
1961 bounds.pop(op->name);
1962 }
1963 return node;
1964 }
1965
1966 Expr visit(const Let *op) override {
1967 lets.emplace_back(op->name, op->value);
1968 Expr expr = visit_let<Expr>(op);
1969 lets.pop_back();
1970 return expr;
1971 }
1972 Stmt visit(const LetStmt *op) override {
1973 return visit_let<Stmt>(op);
1974 }
1975
1976 Expr visit(const Load *op) override {
1977 if (!is_const_one(op->predicate)) {
1978 // TODO(psuriana): We shouldn't mess with predicated load for now.
1979 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1980 }
1981 if (!op->type.is_vector() || op->index.as<Ramp>()) {
1982 // Don't handle scalar or simple vector loads.
1983 return IRMutator::visit(op);
1984 }
1985
1986 Expr index = mutate(op->index);
1987 Interval unaligned_index_bounds = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(index, bounds);
1988 if (unaligned_index_bounds.is_bounded()) {
1989 // We want to try both the unaligned and aligned
1990 // bounds. The unaligned bounds might fit in 256 elements,
1991 // while the aligned bounds do not.
1992 int align = lut_alignment / op->type.bytes();
1993 Interval aligned_index_bounds = {
1994 (unaligned_index_bounds.min / align) * align,
1995 ((unaligned_index_bounds.max + align) / align) * align - 1};
1996 ModulusRemainder alignment(align, 0);
1997
1998 for (const Interval &index_bounds : {aligned_index_bounds, unaligned_index_bounds}) {
1999 Expr index_span = span_of_bounds(index_bounds);
2000 index_span = common_subexpression_elimination(index_span);
2001 index_span = simplify(index_span);
2002
2003 if (can_prove(index_span < 256)) {
2004 // This is a lookup within an up to 256 element array. We
2005 // can use dynamic_shuffle for this.
2006 int const_extent = as_const_int(index_span) ? *as_const_int(index_span) + 1 : 256;
2007 Expr base = simplify(index_bounds.min);
2008
2009 // Load all of the possible indices loaded from the
2010 // LUT. Note that for clamped ramps, this loads up to 1
2011 // vector past the max. CodeGen_Hexagon::allocation_padding
2012 // returns a native vector size to account for this.
2013 Expr lut = Load::make(op->type.with_lanes(const_extent), op->name,
2014 Ramp::make(base, 1, const_extent),
2015 op->image, op->param, const_true(const_extent), alignment);
2016
2017 // We know the size of the LUT is not more than 256, so we
2018 // can safely cast the index to 8 bit, which
2019 // dynamic_shuffle requires.
2020 index = simplify(cast(UInt(8).with_lanes(op->type.lanes()), index - base));
2021 return Call::make(op->type, "dynamic_shuffle", {lut, index, 0, const_extent - 1}, Call::PureIntrinsic);
2022 }
2023 // Only the first iteration of this loop is aligned.
2024 alignment = ModulusRemainder();
2025 }
2026 }
2027 if (!index.same_as(op->index)) {
2028 return Load::make(op->type, op->name, index, op->image, op->param, op->predicate, op->alignment);
2029 } else {
2030 return op;
2031 }
2032 }
2033
2034public:
2035 OptimizeShuffles(int lut_alignment)
2036 : lut_alignment(lut_alignment) {
2037 }
2038};

2040// Distribute constant RHS widening shift lefts as multiplies.
2041// TODO: This is an extremely unfortunate mess. I think the better
2042// solution is for the simplifier to distribute constant multiplications
2043// instead of factoring them, and then this logic is unnecessary (find_mpy_ops
2044// would need to handle shifts, but that's easy).
2045// Another possibility would be adding a widening_mul_add intrinsic that takes
2046// a list of pairs of operands, and computes a widening sum of widening multiplies
2047// of these pairs. FindIntrinsics could aggressively rewrite shifts as
2048// widening_mul_add operands.
2049class DistributeShiftsAsMuls : public IRMutator {
2050private:
2051 static bool is_cast(const Expr &e, Type value_t) {
2052 if (const Cast *cast = e.as<Cast>()) {
2053 return cast->value.type() == value_t;
2054 }
2055 return false;
2056 }
2057
2058 static Expr distribute(const Expr &a, const Expr &b) {
2059 if (const Add *add = a.as<Add>()) {
2060 return Add::make(distribute(add->a, b), distribute(add->b, b));
2061 } else if (const Sub *sub = a.as<Sub>()) {
2062 Expr sub_a = distribute(sub->a, b);
2063 Expr sub_b = distribute(sub->b, b);
2064 Expr negative_sub_b = lossless_negate(sub_b);
2065 if (negative_sub_b.defined()) {
2066 return Add::make(sub_a, negative_sub_b);
2067 } else {
2068 return Sub::make(sub_a, sub_b);
2069 }
2070 } else if (const Cast *cast = a.as<Cast>()) {
2071 Expr cast_b = lossless_cast(b.type().with_bits(cast->value.type().bits()), b);
2072 if (cast_b.defined()) {
2073 Expr mul = widening_mul(cast->value, cast_b);
2074 if (mul.type().bits() <= cast->type.bits()) {
2075 if (mul.type() != cast->type) {
2076 mul = Cast::make(cast->type, mul);
2077 }
2078 return mul;
2079 }
2080 }
2081 } else if (const Call *add = Call::as_intrinsic(a, {Call::widening_add})) {
2082 Expr add_a = Cast::make(add->type, add->args[0]);
2083 Expr add_b = Cast::make(add->type, add->args[1]);
2084 add_a = distribute(add_a, b);
2085 add_b = distribute(add_b, b);
2086 // If add_a and add_b are the same kind of cast, we should remake a widening add.
2087 const Cast *add_a_cast = add_a.as<Cast>();
2088 const Cast *add_b_cast = add_b.as<Cast>();
2089 if (add_a_cast && add_b_cast &&
2090 add_a_cast->value.type() == add->args[0].type() &&
2091 add_b_cast->value.type() == add->args[1].type()) {
2092 return widening_add(add_a_cast->value, add_b_cast->value);
2093 } else {
2094 return Add::make(add_a, add_b);
2095 }
2096 } else if (const Call *sub = Call::as_intrinsic(a, {Call::widening_sub})) {
2097 Expr sub_a = Cast::make(sub->type, sub->args[0]);
2098 Expr sub_b = Cast::make(sub->type, sub->args[1]);
2099 sub_a = distribute(sub_a, b);
2100 sub_b = distribute(sub_b, b);
2101 Expr negative_sub_b = lossless_negate(sub_b);
2102 if (negative_sub_b.defined()) {
2103 sub_b = negative_sub_b;
2104 }
2105 // If sub_a and sub_b are the same kind of cast, we should remake a widening sub.
2106 const Cast *sub_a_cast = sub_a.as<Cast>();
2107 const Cast *sub_b_cast = sub_b.as<Cast>();
2108 if (sub_a_cast && sub_b_cast &&
2109 sub_a_cast->value.type() == sub->args[0].type() &&
2110 sub_b_cast->value.type() == sub->args[1].type()) {
2111 if (negative_sub_b.defined()) {
2112 return widening_add(sub_a_cast->value, sub_b_cast->value);
2113 } else {
2114 return widening_sub(sub_a_cast->value, sub_b_cast->value);
2115 }
2116 } else {
2117 if (negative_sub_b.defined()) {
2118 return Add::make(sub_a, sub_b);
2119 } else {
2120 return Sub::make(sub_a, sub_b);
2121 }
2122 }
2123 } else if (const Call *mul = Call::as_intrinsic(a, {Call::widening_mul})) {
2124 Expr mul_a = Cast::make(mul->type, mul->args[0]);
2125 Expr mul_b = Cast::make(mul->type, mul->args[1]);
2126 mul_a = distribute(mul_a, b);
2127 if (const Cast *mul_a_cast = mul_a.as<Cast>()) {
2128 if (mul_a_cast->value.type() == mul->args[0].type()) {
2129 return widening_mul(mul_a_cast->value, mul->args[1]);
2130 }
2131 }
2132 mul_b = distribute(mul_b, b);
2133 if (const Cast *mul_b_cast = mul_b.as<Cast>()) {
2134 if (mul_b_cast->value.type() == mul->args[1].type()) {
2135 return widening_mul(mul->args[0], mul_b_cast->value);
2136 }
2137 }
2138 }
2139 return simplify(Mul::make(a, b));
2140 }
2141
2142 using IRMutator::visit;
2143
2144 Expr visit(const Call *op) override {
2145 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_left)) {
2146 if (const uint64_t *const_b = as_const_uint(op->args[1])) {
2147 Expr a = op->args[0];
2148 // Only rewrite widening shifts.
2149 const Cast *cast_a = a.as<Cast>();
2150 bool is_widening_cast = cast_a && cast_a->type.bits() >= cast_a->value.type().bits() * 2;
2151 if (is_widening_cast || Call::as_intrinsic(a, {Call::widening_add, Call::widening_mul, Call::widening_sub})) {
2152 return mutate(distribute(a, make_one(a.type()) << *const_b));
2153 }
2154 }
2155 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::widening_shift_left)) {
2156 if (const uint64_t *const_b = as_const_uint(op->args[1])) {
2157 Expr a = Cast::make(op->type, op->args[0]);
2158 return mutate(distribute(a, make_one(a.type()) << *const_b));
2159 }
2160 }
2161 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2162 }
2163};
2164
2165// Try generating vgathers instead of shuffles.
2166// At present, we request VTCM memory with single page allocation flag for all
2167// store_in allocations. So it's always safe to generate a vgather.
2168// Expressions which generate vgathers are of the form:
2169// out(x) = lut(foo(x))
2170// For vgathers out and lut should be in VTCM in a single page.
2171class ScatterGatherGenerator : public IRMutator {
2172 Scope<Interval> bounds;
2173 std::unordered_map<string, const Allocate *> allocations;
2174
2175 using IRMutator::visit;
2176
2177 template<typename NodeType, typename T>
2178 NodeType visit_let(const T *op) {
2179 // We only care about vector lets.
2180 if (op->value.type().is_vector()) {
2181 bounds.push(op->name, bounds_of_expr_in_scope(op->value, bounds));
2182 }
2183 NodeType node = IRMutator::visit(op);
2184 if (op->value.type().is_vector()) {
2185 bounds.pop(op->name);
2186 }
2187 return node;
2188 }
2189
2190 Expr visit(const Let *op) override {
2191 return visit_let<Expr>(op);
2192 }
2193
2194 Stmt visit(const LetStmt *op) override {
2195 return visit_let<Stmt>(op);
2196 }
2197
2198 Stmt visit(const Allocate *op) override {
2199 // Create a map of the allocation
2200 allocations[op->name] = op;
2201 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2202 }
2203
2204 // Try to match expressions of the form:
2205 // out(x) = lut(foo(x))
2206 // to generate vgathers. Here, out and lut should have
2207 // store_in(MemoryType::VTCM) directive. If a vgather is found return Call
2208 // Expr to vgather, otherwise Expr().
2209 Expr make_gather(const Load *op, Expr dst_base, Expr dst_index) {
2210 Type ty = op->type;
2211 const Allocate *alloc = allocations[op->name];
2212 // The lut should be in VTCM.
2213 if (!alloc || alloc->memory_type != MemoryType::VTCM) {
2214 return Expr();
2215 }
2216 // HVX has only 16 or 32-bit gathers. Predicated vgathers are not
2217 // supported yet.
2218 if (op->index.as<Ramp>() || !is_const_one(op->predicate) || !ty.is_vector() ||
2219 ty.bits() == 8) {
2220 return Expr();
2221 }
2222 Expr index = mutate(ty.bytes() * op->index);
2223 Interval index_bounds = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(index, bounds);
2224 if (ty.bits() == 16 && index_bounds.is_bounded()) {
2225 Expr index_span = span_of_bounds(index_bounds);
2226 index_span = common_subexpression_elimination(index_span);
2227 index_span = simplify(index_span);
2228 // We need to downcast the index values to 16 bit signed. So all the
2229 // the indices must be less than 1 << 15.
2230 if (!can_prove(index_span < std::numeric_limits<int16_t>::max())) {
2231 return Expr();
2232 }
2233 }
2234 // Calculate the size of the buffer lut in bytes.
2235 Expr size = ty.bytes();
2236 for (size_t i = 0; i < alloc->extents.size(); i++) {
2237 size *= alloc->extents[i];
2238 }
2239 Expr src = Variable::make(Handle(), op->name);
2240 Expr new_index = mutate(cast(ty.with_code(Type::Int), index));
2241 dst_index = mutate(dst_index);
2242
2243 return Call::make(ty, "gather", {std::move(dst_base), dst_index, src, size - 1, new_index},
2244 Call::Intrinsic);
2245 }
2246
2247 // Checks if the Store node can be replaced with a scatter_accumulate.
2248 // If yes, return new_value to be used for scatter-accumulate, else return
2249 // the input parameter value.
2250 Expr is_scatter_acc(const Store *op) {
2251 Expr lhs = Load::make(op->value.type(), op->name, op->index, Buffer<>(),
2252 Parameter(), const_true(op->value.type().lanes()), op->alignment);
2253 Expr wild = Variable::make(op->value.type(), "*");
2254 vector<Expr> matches;
2255 if (expr_match(lhs + wild, op->value, matches) ||
2256 expr_match(wild + lhs, op->value, matches)) {
2257 // Scatter accumulate found.
2258 return matches[0];
2259 }
2260 return op->value;
2261 }
2262
2263 Stmt visit(const Store *op) override {
2264 // HVX has only 16 or 32-bit gathers. Predicated vgathers are not
2265 // supported yet.
2266 Type ty = op->value.type();
2267 if (!is_const_one(op->predicate) || !ty.is_vector() || ty.bits() == 8) {
2268 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2269 }
2270 // To use vgathers, the destination address must be VTCM memory.
2271 const Allocate *alloc = allocations[op->name];
2272 if (!alloc || alloc->memory_type != MemoryType::VTCM) {
2273 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2274 }
2275 // The source for a gather must also be a buffer in VTCM.
2276 if (op->index.as<Ramp>() && op->value.as<Load>()) {
2277 // Check for vgathers
2278 Expr dst_base = Variable::make(Handle(), op->name);
2279 Expr dst_index = op->index.as<Ramp>()->base;
2280 Expr value = make_gather(op->value.as<Load>(), dst_base, dst_index);
2281 if (value.defined()) {
2282 // Found a vgather.
2283 // Function make_gather already mutates all the call arguements,
2284 // so no need to mutate again.
2285 return Evaluate::make(value);
2286 }
2287 }
2288 // Check for scatter/scatter-accumulate.
2289 if (op->index.as<Ramp>()) {
2290 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2291 }
2292 // Calculate the size of the buffer in bytes.
2293 Expr size = ty.bytes();
2294 for (size_t i = 0; i < alloc->extents.size(); i++) {
2295 size *= alloc->extents[i];
2296 }
2297 // Check for scatter-acc.
2298 Expr value = is_scatter_acc(op);
2299 Call::IntrinsicOp intrinsic = Call::hvx_scatter;
2300 if (!value.same_as(op->value)) {
2301 // It's a scatter-accumulate
2302 intrinsic = Call::hvx_scatter_acc;
2303 }
2304 Expr buffer = Variable::make(Handle(), op->name);
2305 Expr index = mutate(cast(ty.with_code(Type::Int), ty.bytes() * op->index));
2306 value = mutate(value);
2307 Stmt scatter = Evaluate::make(Call::make(ty, intrinsic,
2308 {buffer, size - 1, index, value}, Call::Intrinsic));
2309 return scatter;
2310 }
2311};

2313// Scatter-Gather instructions on Hexagon are asynchronous and hence require a
2314// scatter-release store followed by a vector load from the same address. This
2315// stalls the pipeline untill all previous scatter-gather operations have
2316// finished. The operations are not ordered with respect to load and store
2317// operations as well.
2318class SyncronizationBarriers : public IRMutator {
2319 // Keep track of all scatter-gather operations in flight which could cause
2320 // a hazard in the future.
2321 std::map<string, vector<const Stmt *>> in_flight;
2322 // Trail of For Blocks to reach a stmt.
2323 vector<const Stmt *> curr_path;
2324 // Current Stmt being mutated.
2325 const Stmt *curr = nullptr;
2326 // Track where the Stmt generated a scatter-release.
2327 std::map<const Stmt *, Expr> sync;
2328
2329 using IRMutator::visit;
2330
2331 Expr visit(const Call *op) override {
2332 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::hvx_scatter) ||
2333 op->is_intrinsic(Call::hvx_scatter_acc) ||
2334 op->is_intrinsic(Call::hvx_gather)) {
2335 string name = op->args[0].as<Variable>()->name;
2336 // Check if the scatter-gather encountered conflicts with any
2337 // previous operation. If yes, insert a scatter-release.
2338 check_hazard(name);
2339 in_flight[name] = curr_path;
2340 }
2341 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2342 }
2343
2344 Stmt visit(const For *op) override {
2345 // Keep trail of the For blocks encoutered.
2346 curr_path.push_back(curr);
2347 Stmt s = IRMutator::visit(op);
2348 curr_path.pop_back();
2349 return s;
2350 }
2351
2352 // Creates entry in sync map for the stmt requiring a
2353 // scatter-release instruction before it.
2354 void check_hazard(const string &name) {
2355 if (in_flight.find(name) == in_flight.end()) {
2356 return;
2357 }
2358 // Sync Needed. Add the scatter-release before the first different For
2359 // loop lock between the curr_path and the hazard src location.
2360 size_t min_size = std::min(in_flight[name].size(), curr_path.size());
2361 size_t i = 0;
2362 // Find the first different For loop block.
2363 for (; i < min_size; i++) {
2364 if (in_flight[name][i] != curr_path[i]) {
2365 break;
2366 }
2367 }
2368 if (i < curr_path.size()) {
2369 // Place scatter-release before the first different For loop block.
2370 sync[curr_path[i]] = Variable::make(Handle(), name);
2371 } else {
2372 // Need to add the scatter-release before the curr stmt.
2373 sync[curr] = Variable::make(Handle(), name);
2374 }
2375 in_flight.clear();
2376 }
2377
2378 Expr visit(const Load *op) override {
2379 // Resolve scatter-load hazard.
2380 check_hazard(op->name);
2381 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2382 }
2383
2384 Stmt visit(const Store *op) override {
2385 // Resolve scatter-store and gather-store hazards.
2386 check_hazard(op->name);
2387 return IRMutator::visit(op);
2388 }
2389
2390public:
2391 using IRMutator::mutate;
2392
2393 Stmt mutate(const Stmt &s) override {
2394 curr = &s;
2395 Stmt new_s = IRMutator::mutate(s);
2396 // Wrap the stmt with scatter-release if any hazard was detected.
2397 if (sync.find(&s) != sync.end()) {
2398 Stmt scatter_sync =
2399 Evaluate::make(Call::make(Int(32), Call::hvx_scatter_release, {sync[&s]}, Call::Intrinsic));
2400 return Block::make(scatter_sync, new_s);
2401 }
2402 return new_s;
2403 }
2404};

2408Stmt optimize_hexagon_shuffles(const Stmt &s, int lut_alignment) {
2409 // Replace indirect and other complicated loads with
2410 // dynamic_shuffle (vlut) calls.
2411 return OptimizeShuffles(lut_alignment).mutate(s);

2413
2414Stmt scatter_gather_generator(Stmt s) {
2415 // Generate vscatter-vgather instruction if target >= v65
2416 s = substitute_in_all_lets(s);
2417 s = ScatterGatherGenerator().mutate(s);
2418 s = SyncronizationBarriers().mutate(s);
2419 s = common_subexpression_elimination(s);
2420 return s;
2421}
2422
2423Stmt optimize_hexagon_instructions(Stmt s, const Target &t) {
2424 // We need to redo intrinsic matching due to simplification that has
2425 // happened after the end of target independent lowering.
2426 s = find_intrinsics(s);
2427
2428 // Hexagon prefers widening shifts to be expressed as multiplies to
2429 // hopefully hit compound widening multiplies.
2430 s = DistributeShiftsAsMuls().mutate(s);
2431
2432 // Pattern match VectorReduce IR node. Handle vector reduce instructions
2433 // before OptimizePatterns to prevent being mutated by patterns like
2434 // (v0 + v1 * c) -> add_mpy
2435 s = VectorReducePatterns().mutate(s);
2436
2437 // Peephole optimize for Hexagon instructions. These can generate
2438 // interleaves and deinterleaves alongside the HVX intrinsics.
2439 s = OptimizePatterns(t).mutate(s);
2440
2441 // Try to eliminate any redundant interleave/deinterleave pairs.
2442 s = EliminateInterleaves(t.natural_vector_size(Int(8))).mutate(s);
2443
2444 // There may be interleaves left over that we can fuse with other
2445 // operations.
2446 s = FuseInterleaves().mutate(s);
2447 return s;
2448}
